├── sweep.sh              ← W&B sweep launcher
│
├── optimizers/
│   ├── fopng.py          ← FOPNG — Fisher-Orthogonal Projected Natural Gradient
│   ├── ewc.py            ← EWC — Elastic Weight Consolidation baseline
│   └── adam.py           ← Adam baseline (no forgetting protection)
│
├── tasks/
│   ├── split_mnist.py    ← Split-MNIST: 5 binary tasks (0v1, 2v3, 4v5, 6v7, 8v9)
│   ├── permuted_mnist.py ← Permuted-MNIST: 10+ random permutation tasks
│   └── split_cifar10.py  ← Split-CIFAR-10: 5 tasks on natural images
│
├── visualizations/       ← Trajectory plots and per-task accuracy graphs
├── data/                 ← Auto-populated on first run
└── wandb/                ← W&B run logs (auto-populated)
```

---

## The Method

FOPNG combines two ideas, applied to the compact hypernetwork parameter set φ:

**1 — Natural Gradient**

Standard gradient descent treats all parameter directions as equal. The Fisher information matrix captures how sensitively the model's output *distribution* responds to each parameter. Natural gradient preconditioning makes update steps equal-sized in *distribution space* rather than Euclidean space — a more faithful measure of how much the model actually changes.

**2 — Orthogonal Projection**

After each task, its gradient is stored in a memory matrix G. New updates are projected onto the **Fisher-orthogonal complement** of G — directions that are geometrically guaranteed not to disturb prior task outputs. This is a hard constraint, not a soft penalty.

Applied to the hypernetwork φ rather than the full target network, both the Fisher matrix and gradient memory stay tractable regardless of target network size.

---

## Baselines

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| **Adam** | Naive baseline — no forgetting protection, establishes the lower bound |
| **EWC** | Diagonal Fisher penalty on important weights, operates in Euclidean space |
| **OGD** | Euclidean orthogonal gradient projection — closest analogue to FOPNG |
| **FNG** | Natural gradient without orthogonal projection |

---

## Benchmarks

| Benchmark | Tasks | Input dim | Notes |
|-----------|-------|-----------|-------|
| Split-MNIST | 5 binary | 784 | Entry-level sequential learning |
| Permuted-MNIST | 10+ | 784 | Long-horizon retention test |
| Split-CIFAR-10 | 5 | 3072 | Natural images, higher complexity |
| Split-CIFAR-100 | 20 | 3072 | 100 classes, hardest benchmark |

---

## Usage

```bash
cd HyperFisher

# Split-MNIST with all three methods
python main.py \
  --task split_mnist \
  --methods fopng ewc adam \
  --model HyperNetwork \
  --epochs 5 \
  --lr 1e-3

# Split-CIFAR-10, FOPNG only, larger gradient memory
python main.py \
  --task split_cifar10 \
  --methods fopng \
  --model HyperNetwork \
  --epochs 10 \
  --grads_per_task 40 \
  --max_directions 200

# W&B hyperparameter sweep
bash sweep.sh
```

**Key CLI arguments**

| Argument | Default | Description |
|----------|---------|-------------|
| `--task` | required | `split_mnist` · `permuted_mnist` · `split_cifar10` |
| `--methods` | `fopng adam` | Any of: `fopng` `ewc` `adam` `ogd` `fng` |
| `--model` | `HyperNetwork` | `HyperNetwork` or `MLP` |
| `--epochs` | `10` | Epochs per task |
| `--lr` | `1e-3` | Learning rate |
| `--lam` | `1e-3` | EWC regularization strength |
| `--grads_per_task` | `40` | Gradient directions stored per task |
| `--max_directions` | `80` | Hard cap on memory matrix columns |
| `--embedding_dim` | `4` | Task embedding dimension |
| `--hyper_hidden_dim` | `16` | Hypernetwork bottleneck width |

---

## Preliminary Results

> Split-MNIST · Full Hypernetwork · 5 sequential binary tasks

Final per-task accuracy after training on all 5 tasks:

| Method | T1 | T2 | T3 | T4 | T5 | **Avg** |
|--------|:--:|:--:|:--:|:--:|:--:|:-------:|
| Adam (baseline) | 100% | 50% | 97% | 47% | 98% | 78% |
| EWC | 52% | 56% | 48% | 98% | 97% | 70% |
| **FOPNG (ours)** | **100%** | **97%** | **93%** | **99%** | **97%** | **97%** |

FOPNG maintains near-perfect accuracy across all tasks with minimal forgetting. Adam collapses on previously learned tasks within a few steps. EWC partially mitigates forgetting but degrades under longer task sequences.

---

## Installation

```bash
git clone --recurse-submodules <repo-url>
cd HyperFisher
pip install torch torchvision wandb
```

GPU is recommended — the code detects CUDA automatically and falls back to CPU. Datasets download automatically on first run into `HyperFisher/data/`.

